<DOC><DOCNO> AP900525-0042 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-90 0332EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-25 0241</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0249</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Sharply Lower; Tokyo Stocks Up</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar declined sharply against the yen Friday,while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange continued to rise.   The dollar closed at 150.05 yen, down 1.38 yen from Thursday'sclose of 151.43 yen. After opening at 150.45 yen, the currencyranged between 149.90 yen and 150.85 yen.   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 482.13points, or 1.49 percent, closing the week at 32,793.88. The Nikkeiindex gained 135.24 points on Thursday.   In the bond market, the price of the benchmark No. 119 10-yearJapanese government bonds edged higher to 88.30 points as of 3 p.m.(2 a.m. EDT), up from Thursday's close of 87.76. The yield fell to6.890 percent, down from the previous day's 7.010 percent.   Currency dealers said the dollar's retreat followed itsovernight decline in New York, where it finished at 151.15 yen,down from 151.45 yen on Wednesday.   Masaki Shikada, a dealer with Fuji Bank, said the dollar movedupward slightly during early trading on buying by institutionalinvestors, including life insurance firms.   ``But the dollar then stayed at a 150.70-.80 yen range'' in theabsence of fresh news, Shikada said.   Stocks moved up gradually in a favorable reaction to the yen'sappreciation against the dollar, traders said.   ``Issues centering on large-capital stocks attracted buyers'attention, encouraged by the high yen,'' a Nomura Securitiesanalyst said on condition of anonymity.</TEXT></DOC>